# Deploying

This app is a plain Go HTTP server that serves **Server-Sent Events**. It runs
anywhere a container runs — the scaffolding here is intentionally
platform-neutral.

## Build and run locally

```sh
make build                      # compile templ + Elm into static/elm.js
docker compose up --build       # http://localhost:8080
```

`docker build` compiles templ and Go inside the image, but the **Elm bundle must
already exist** (`static/elm.js`) because Elm has no reliable in-container
cross-arch compiler. `make build` produces it; CI does the same before building
the image.

## Continuous delivery

`.github/workflows/deploy.yml` runs on every push and pull request:

1. **test** — installs Elm, runs `make build`, `go vet`, and `go test`.
2. **image** — on pushes to `main` and `v*` tags, builds the container and
   pushes it to **GitHub Container Registry** at `ghcr.io/<owner>/<repo>`.

It authenticates with the built-in `GITHUB_TOKEN`, so there are no secrets to
configure. Pull the published image and run it on any host:

```sh
docker run -p 8080:8080 ghcr.io/<owner>/<repo>:latest
```

## SSE: the one thing to get right

The broker holds a long-lived SSE connection per browser tab. Whatever you put
in front of the container **must not buffer responses**:

- The server already sends `Cache-Control: no-cache` and `X-Accel-Buffering: no`
  and flushes after every event — nginx/ingress honour the latter.
- For other proxies, disable response buffering explicitly (e.g. nginx
  `proxy_buffering off;`).
- Allow long idle timeouts; SSE streams stay open between events.
- Prefer HTTP/2 at the edge: it multiplexes many streams over one connection,
  avoiding the browser's ~6-connections-per-host limit when a page opens
  several streams.
- If your platform scales to zero, keep at least one instance warm or accept
  that idle clients will reconnect (the broker re-hydrates on reconnect).

`PORT` is read from the environment (default `8080`).
